a conduction system disorder that refers to abnormalities in SN impulse formation and propagation and includes sinus bradycardia, sinus pause/arrest, chronotropic incompetence, and sinoatrial exit block.
a coronary artery disorder AE that takes place in or is related to the coronary inside the heart
a myocardial infarction AE in which the inferior wall of the heart is involved. It is often caused by occlusion of the right coronary artery.

a myocardial infarction AE in which the anterior wall of the heart is involved. Anterior wall myocardial infarction is often caused by occlusion of the left anterior descending coronary artery. It can be categorized as anteroseptal or anterolateral wall myocardial infarction.
a hematology investigation result abnormal AE that is characterized by an abnormal blast cell count
a blast cell count abnormal AE that is characterized by a decreased blast cell count
a hematology investigation result abnormal AE that is characterized by an abnormal platelet count
a platelet count abnormal AE that is characterized by an increased platelet count
a white blood cell profile abnormal AE that is characterized by an abnormal eosinophil count
an eosinophil count abnormal AE that is characterized by a decreased eosinophil count
a hypertension AE that is characterized by high blood pressure in the systemic arteries - the vessels that carry blood from the heart to the body's tissues (other than the lungs).
a hypotension AE that has an outcome of a decrease in the amount of pressure the heart generates when pumping blood through arteries to the rest of the body

a cardiac valve disease AE that is characterized by an impaired function of a papillary muscle, usually due to ischemia or infarction, with resulting incompetence of the mitral (rarely tricuspid) valve.
a hypertension AE that has an outcome of an increase in the amount of pressure in the arteries when the heart is at rest between beats
a hypertension AE that has an outcome of an increase in the amount of pressure the heart generates when pumping blood through arteries to the rest of the body

a cardiac ventricular disorder AE that is a condition in nwhich the right ventricle of the heart was functionally impaired. This condition usually leads to heart failure or myocardial infarction, and other cardiovascular complicationns.
an arrhythmia AE that is characterized by a premature contraction of the ventricle
an embolism disorder AE that is a result of an obstruction in a cardiac vessel due to a blood clot or other foreign matters
a vascular disorder AE that is characterized by an obstruction in a blood vessel due to a blood clot or other foreign matter that gets stuck while traveling through the bloodstream.

an adverse event causity that represents a retrodictrive causal relation between an adverse event and a medical intervention. Specifically, it addresses this question: given an individual who has received a medical intervention and developed the adverse event, was the event caused by the medical intervention?

an arrhythmia AE that results in extra, abnormal heartbeats that begin in one of the heart's two lower pumping chambers (ventricles). These extra beats disrupt the regular heart rhythm, sometimes causing the patient to feel a flip-flop or skipped beat in the chest.
a cardiac valve disease AE that is charaterized by the backflow of blood from the pulmonary artery into the right ventricle, owing to imperfect functioning of the pulmonary valve
a cardiac vavle disease AE that is characterized by a congenital heart defect in which blood flow from the heart to the pulmonary artery is blocked
a vasculitis AE that is an inflammation specific to an artery or arteries
a process quality that represents the level of severity of an adverse event.
a vascular disorder AE that results in an abnormal widening or ballooning of a portion of an artery due to weakness in the wall of the blood vessel
a vascular disorder that affects the veins or blood circulation of the veins
an aneurysm AE that results in the weakening of the balloon-like bulge that the blood pressure causes the artery wall to leak or burst
an aneurysm AE that refers to an aneurysm involving cardiac tissue. This most often occurs as a ventricular aneurysm following a myocardial infarction
an aneurysm AE that occurs in the aorta
an aneurysm ruptured AE that occurs in the aorta

an aortic disorder AE in which there is a separation of the aorta walls. The small tear can become larger. It can lead to bleeding into and along the wall of the aorta, the major artery carrying blood out of the heart.

an aneurysm ruptured AE that occurs in the brain where blood spurts into the subarachnoid space under arterial pressure, continuing until increased local or generalized intracranial pressure stops the bleeding.
an aneurysm AE that occurs in the brain
a thrombosis AE that is a rare lesion and may be defined as a thrombosis of a vessel without any obvious underlying cause that occurs in the aorta
an arterial thrombosis AE that is characterized by the occurrence of a thrombus in the carotid arteries (two large blood vessels that supply oxygenated blood to the large, front part of the brain)
an arterial embolism AE that occurs in the cerebral artery
an arterial thrombosis AE that occurs in the cerebral artery, also referred to as an embolism AE

a venous thrombosis AE that is characterized by thrombosis of the venous channels in the brain. It is an uncommon cause of cerebral infarction relative to arterial disease, but it is an important consideration because of its potential morbidity.

a venous thrombosis AE that occurs when a blood clot forms in the brain’s venous sinuses that prevents blood from draining out of the brain. As a result, blood cells may break and leak blood into the brain tissues, forming a hemorrhage.
an embolism AE that is caused by a gas bubble that enters the vein

a thrombosis that is characterized by a clot that blocks blood flow a mesenteric vein, one of two veins through which blood leaves the intestine. The condition interrupts the blood supply to the intestine and can result in damage to the intestines.
